Stack the decorators on the controller method and document the DTO via class properties. ```ts
@ApiTags('invoices')
@Controller({ path: 'invoices', version: '1' })
export class InvoicesController {
  @Post()
  @HttpCode(201)
  @ApiOperation({ summary: 'Create an invoice', operationId: 'createInvoice' })
  @ApiBody({ type: InvoiceCreateDto })
  @ApiResponse({ status: 201, description: 'Created', type: Invoice })
  @ApiResponse({ status: 400, description: 'Validation error', type: ErrorResponseDto })
  @ApiResponse({ status: 409, description: 'Duplicate invoice number', type: ErrorResponseDto })
  create(@Body() dto: InvoiceCreateDto): Promise<Invoice> { ... }
}
``` On the DTO, every field uses `@ApiProperty({ example, description })` (or `@ApiPropertyOptional`) so the schema generates with realistic examples — `class-validator` decorators stay on the same property and the Nest Swagger plugin merges them into the OpenAPI spec. Use a shared `ErrorResponseDto` for all non-2xx responses so the contract is consistent across endpoints. Set `operationId` per route so generated clients have stable method names. Bootstrap with `SwaggerModule.setup('docs', app, document)` behind an auth guard in non-dev. Cite `25-documentation-swagger.md` and `09-validation.md`.

DTOs plus `class-validator` decorators (`@IsString`, `@Length`, `@IsEmail`, `@IsUUID`, `@IsEnum`, etc.) are the choke point where unknown fields, bad types, and injection payloads are stopped. Skip validation on one route and you have implicitly told that route to trust the client — which is exactly the OWASP class A03 (Injection) and A08 (Software/Data Integrity Failures) starting condition, plus mass-assignment risk where an attacker passes `isAdmin: true` and your ORM happily writes it. Configure the global `ValidationPipe` once in `main.ts`: ```ts
app.useGlobalPipes(new ValidationPipe({
  whitelist: true,
  forbidNonWhitelisted: true,
  transform: true,
  transformOptions: { enableImplicitConversion: true },
  forbidUnknownValues: true,
  stopAtFirstError: false,
}));
``` `whitelist: true` strips any property not declared on the DTO so unknown fields cannot ride into the service or ORM (the mass-assignment defense). `forbidNonWhitelisted: true` upgrades stripping to a `400` error so silent data loss is impossible. `transform: true` (with `enableImplicitConversion`) coerces `string` query params to typed primitives so `@IsInt()` actually means int. Add `disableErrorMessages: true` in production if your error details leak constraint internals. Pair with class-transformer `@Type(() => Date)` for nested objects. Cite `09-validation.md` and `11-security.md`.
